Aug 31 2008 	One of my all-time global favorites	I had stayed at Dukes some years ago on previous business trips to London but more recently had to eschew the hotel as the rate, converted into dollars, was way beyond what my companies would pay. But when I realized I could grab a special rate from the hotel's web site for my most recent visit, I didn't think twice about booking. I had recalled Dukes as a stellar, efficient and no nonsense old-style hotel. It still is, but without being pretentious. The rooms are comfortable, clean and nicely decorated. The bathroom is a combination of the 19th and late 20th century. Only complaint I had was a dripping water outlet in the tub. Another quibble is the digital television system, obviously being run through some sort of computer server. It takes time to boot and seems to freeze frequently on start-up. Internet access is offered at two speeds and the full-on broadband package is among the most expensive rates I've seen for any hotel anywhere. Much to my surprise the hotel seemed filled with fellow Americans, who I thought would have looked for other accommodations to stretch their dollar. Dukes is worth a visit just for its legendary bar. The sky's the limit on what you could end up paying for a shot here as bottles in the locked glass cabinet date back to 1800. There's an impressive selection of 19th century champagne and armagnac, as well as some -- by comparison -- reasonably priced 20th century single malt whiskeys. The creator of James Bond (007), Ian Fleming, was a regular here. So perhaps this is the place which inspired &quot;shaken, not stirred.&quot; Dukes will certainly shake your budget if you decide to sleep, dine and wine there, but it will also certainly stir the soul of even the most jaded world traveller.	
