Sep 18 2006 	Cute hotel	This is a cute hotel: small, in a quiet tiny cul-de-sac which itself is off a small side street, well presented on the outside and welcoming staff. Check in was swift and efficient. The lobby is traditional in style. Walking to the room, one immediately hears lots of squeeky floorboards - and the rooms are full of them too - it's definitely an old hotel underneath!The first room we had was small but well proportioned, especially given its central london location. Flat screen TV, comfy bed and pillows, soft luxurious furnishings. The rain shower was a good feature. The Molton Brown toiletries were lovely to use and there were so many little useful things in the bathroom. However, the air conditioning drove us both mad during our stay - it sounded just like an old rattly fridge compressor. It was powerful and the room was lovely and cool during the hot weather but I have never stayed in a five star hotel with such a rattly A/C! This unfortunately spoiled my first night's sleep (picture lying awake at 4am listening to the rattle! but so tired...!!) and the reception staff were very apologetic and transferred us to another room in the basement. This was not as modern as the one on the ground floor - old style TV, no minibar - but otherwise much the same and in fact it was quieter down there. Unfortunately, this one's air conditioning also rattled a little but MUCH less than the first, so we just ignored it and to be fair, I slept well the second night, although I was rather exhausted from a long day sightseeing and shopping. I would actually have expected more &quot;redress&quot; or compensation after a distressing experience like a bad night's sleep - this is a 5* place after all. A couple of years ago I remember having a bad mattress in One Aldwych and it spoiled my night's sleep and the next day they moved us to a lovely suite and moved all our things to the new room themselves without us packing a thing! Outstanding service.The dining room is also cute and well presented, and there is a gym/health club for residents' use.Car parking was expensive at £54 per 24 hours but is valet parking. I believe. About 5 mins by taxi we found an offer for £10 per day on the weekend: Masterpark by the Houses of Parliament. Useful if you're there all weekend.Overall, excellent location and service, nice comfy rooms but they really must service their air conditioners. Also, if there is a fault with the room that really upsets a customer (not just a minor niggle), staff should be encouraged to offer something by way of apology: nicer room, maybe a breakfast or even just a bottle of house wine - at least something!	
Sep 11 2006 	Charming	The Dukes feels like a traditional house in the country in the middle of St James. My room was a good size and well decorated (small bathroom). Nice attention to detail throughout the hotel. Service about as good as you can get in London these days. Breakfast is served in an elegant room, and all items are chosen with care, although the choice is a little limited.The hotel has just come under a different management company. They should be careful not to &quot;standardise&quot; the delicate balance of a place like the Dukes, but here are some suggested improvements that would better justify the room rates: welcome drink and fruit or pastries, better and larger toiletries, flat screen TV + CD player, more TV and radio channels, better turndown service, more items supplied in the rooms (slippers, shoe horn, etc.), more choice for breakfast. Overall, a very charming experiences in the best part of London.	
