May 18 2006 	One of London's Secrets!	We stay at Dukes regularly, usually for one to three nights at a time. Several of the front office staff have got to know us and even after several months away they recognize us by name. This does not happen in most London hotels! The location is close to my company's HQ but this is not the only reason we choose Dukes. We have found other hotels to lack the personal service.As noted above, we find the front office staff to be most friendly and have to wonder about some of the negative comments in this regard. We have found them to be remarkably patient when dealing with some very tiresome guests!The reception area smells wonderful as there is always a scented votive burning - this gives a unique sensory welcome to the hotel. Decoration is superb and is a good mix of traditional (furniture) and modern (floral decorations).The bar is justifiably famous but very expensive. The staff are from Italy and very friendly. We have never had a problem getting a table there even though it always looks full!Believe it or not, we have never eaten a meal in the hotel. I don't think the restaurant is one of the hotel's strong points and the fact that the staff are eager to make restaurant bookings elsewhere kind of supports that opinion! There are so many good choices for breakfast as well as lunch and dinner that there is no real need to order anything more than an early morning tray of tea and/or coffee (beautifully presented). The staff don't seem to mind you bringing in coffee and pastries from Starbucks or Pret a Manger (both close by).The rooms are variable in size and some are quite small. They are constantly being upgraded and flat panel TVs are a new addition. The beds are as you might expect - very comfortable mattress with fine linen and pillows to match. Most rooms are very quiet but we have experienced the early morning trash collection cacophony a few times!We have cell phones so do not use the hotel phone to call out. Internet usage (wire and wireless) is available but also very expensive.The bathrooms are always beautifully clean and well kitted out. The in-bath showers are very powerfull and vertical so it is difficult to take a shower without getting one's hair wet. Also, the slope of the bath makes it quite difficult to stand under the shower head. As others have mentioned, getting in and out of the bath tub is not always easy for older people.To summarize, a great London boutique hotel, Dukes is expensive but worth it!	
